{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/simpsons-paradox-decae6a4de88", "time": 1682996291.753521, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/simpsons-paradox-decae6a4de88/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Simpson\u2019s Paradox. Understanding A Statistical Illusion | by Guido Vivaldi | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Simpson\u2019s Paradox", "description": "Simpson\u2019s Paradox is a cloquial term for situations when group level trends are hidden or reversed when analyzed at a global level. These are fum examples to think through, and are prime candidates\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://\u201cUsing Mixed-Effects Models For Linear Regression\u201d by Tony Pistilli https://link.medium.com/hFXMRKZlMW", "anchor_text": "previous post", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simpson%27s_paradox", "anchor_text": "Wikipedia article", "paragraph_index": 1}], "all_paragraphs": ["Simpson\u2019s Paradox is a cloquial term for situations when group level trends are hidden or reversed when analyzed at a global level. These are fum examples to think through, and are prime candidates for a mixed-effect model, subject of my previous post.", "An example from the Wikipedia article for this topic is below: the blue and red groups have a clear positive trend, however regressing the two groups with one line produces a negative trend.", "A similar reality commonly occurs when analyzing healthcare claims trends (and is certainly extendable to other industries). In the image below 4 medical services are shown\u200a\u2014\u200atwo Inpatient, which are more expensive because of the resulting multi-day stay, and two Outpatient. A common healthplan program seeks to move lower intensity/lower cost Inpatient services into an Outpatient setting: doing so saves members significant amounts of money in deductible/coinsurance payments. This produces a fascinating trend though, because the low intensity Inpatient services are often higher intensity with respect to otherwise low intensity Outpatient services.", "The two sections represent utilization per year per thousand people (a common metric to adjust out for membership growth/decay when analyzing utilization), and cost per unit (which is often called \u201cCost/Mix\u201d because aggregations of the field can hide changes in utilization of underlying services without any cost per unit changes.", "As the chart moves from period 1 (P1) to period 2 (P2), 50 units of the inexpensive Inpatient treatment were moved to Outpatient, where they are relatively more expensive. The unit cost for each service is unchanged. Overall these 50 units now cost $9,000 where they previously cost $12,000, however the underlying trends are deceiving. Both unit cost trends increase due to a higher proportion of high cost services in each bucket. The Inpatient utilization trend decreases, offset by Outpatient. At the IP/OP level, this initiative looks like a disaster! Looking at the total level lines up better with reality: utilization is unchanged, but some services are now lower cost.", "Simpson\u2019s Paradox is easy to work around if you identify it is present. In my mixed-effect model post we identified this by testing for homoscedasticity in our data and analyzing residual plots. In the Wikipedia picture above, you could notice that the residuals for each group go from negativs to positive as the x-axis moves left to right\u200a\u2014\u200athis correlation in your residuals is a good sign you\u2019re missing something.", "This underscore the importance of data visualization and explanatory data analysis as well. We can end this post noting that while a picture is worth a thousand words, some pictures need a thousand word explanation\u200a\u2014\u200athat is the value of the data scientist and analytics profession.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Healthcare actuary and data scientist fascinated by applications of predictive analytics and machine learning to healthcare."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fdecae6a4de88&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsimpsons-paradox-decae6a4de88&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsimpsons-paradox-decae6a4de88&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsimpsons-paradox-decae6a4de88&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsimpsons-paradox-decae6a4de88&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/?source=post_page-----decae6a4de88--------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/?source=post_page-----decae6a4de88--------------------------------", "anchor_t